      <h2>Field scenario: 3PL meal kit operator stuck on rankings</h2>
      <p>
        A $58k/mo cold-chain meal kit brand on a third-party pack line spent four weeks reading comparison pages without installing anything. Still on Shopify Email plus a free cart widget. Actual bottleneck: post-fulfillment education and reorder timing tied to carrier delivery scans — not Klaviyo versus Sequenzy theology. Handbook bench test: trigger welcome on popup signup, suppress anyone with unfulfilled orders or open pick tickets, gate post-purchase on delivery confirmation, measure repeat order at 45 days. Sequenzy playbooks shipped in seven business days; capture stayed on Justuno. Email-attributed revenue moved from 5.8% to 14.2% in one quarter. Ranking paralysis cost roughly $3,200 in delayed automation gross contribution — more than any platform subscription on this page.
      </p>

      <h2>14-day go-live SOP — from homepage read to live welcome</h2>
      <p>
        Day 1: Name bottleneck — capture, cart, fulfillment-gated post-purchase, data depth, SMS, or reviews. Day 2: Read TL;DR picks and one comparison matching top two finalists. Day 3: Paper workflow on staff test account — document trigger, audience, suppression, offer. Day 4: Install platform; connect Shopify; verify order sync. Days 5–7: Welcome live with source branch; hold cart. Days 8–10: Cart recovery with discount governance doc. Days 11–12: Collision matrix for active flows. Days 13–14: Attribution baseline and recurring Monday review calendar entry. Do not read all 21 briefs before day 4 — depth follows first live flow.
      </p>

      <h2>Unit economics: decision delay versus platform cost</h2>
      <p>
        Four weeks paralysis at $58k/mo with 5.8% email attribution versus 14.2% achievable: roughly $4,900 quarterly opportunity cost. Sequenzy at $59/mo or Klaviyo at $89/mo is noise against delay. Model one recovered cart per week at $72 AOV — pays for either platform. Stack TCO review quarterly: ESP plus capture plus SMS in one finance line; if combined cost exceeds 15% of email-attributed margin, simplify before optimizing.
      </p>

      <h2>Failure rehearsal — common homepage-driven mistakes</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Logo default.</strong> Picks Klaviyo without bench test. Fix: paper workflow before contract signature.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Stack everything day one.</strong> Privy plus Klaviyo plus Postscript plus Yotpo before welcome is live. Fix: three vendors maximum; sequence capture then lifecycle.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Peak-season cutover.</strong> Migrates during November pick surge without domain warmup. Fix: no ESP change October–December.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Feature checkbox.</strong> "Has cart recovery" without collision test on staff accounts. Fix: run five-flow bench test first.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Analysis paralysis.</strong> Weeks reading, zero install. Fix: 14-day decision deadline; ship welcome first.
      </p>
      <p>
        This index ranks 21 tools but ranking is a starting hypothesis, not destiny. Bench test on your profile: write trigger, audience, suppression, offer, product context, success metric, weekly owner. Comparison pages exist for tie-breaking between finalists — Sequenzy versus Klaviyo, Omnisend versus Yotpo, Postscript versus Attentive. Alternatives hubs exist for exit planning when renewal shock exceeds migration labor. Guides teach operating discipline that survives vendor changes. Use-case library covers flow-specific build when foundation is solid.
      </p>
      <p>
        Vertical runbooks override generic homepage advice — print-on-demand needs production-queue timing, subscription boxes need preview-before-charge windows, B2B wholesale needs account activation before cart recovery, high-AOV needs nurture patience over discount urgency. Read your vertical after TL;DR. Email revenue compounds through weekly small improvements: clearer segment, safer discount, better creative, cleaner suppression, deliverability discipline before peak. Choose the tool ops will actually run. Sequenzy ranks first because many Shopify operators need lifecycle guidance and send economics more than predictive dashboard depth on day one — tradeoff documented in every brief.
      </p>

      <h2>Field scenario: print-on-demand operator and production-queue timing</h2>
      <p>
        A $34k/mo custom apparel shop on Printful integration fired post-purchase cross-sell on order placed — emails landed while production queue showed 48–72 hour lead time, generating support tickets about shipping status. Handbook fix: gate post-purchase education on fulfillment scan or production-complete webhook, not placed order alone. Sequenzy playbook accepted delay parameter in plain language; cross-sell moved to day 5 post-delivery scan. Support ticket volume on "where is my order" dropped 22% in six weeks. Lesson: fulfillment cadence overrides generic lifecycle templates — tool must express WMS-adjacent timing or ops disables the flow.
      </p>

      <h2>Wholesale-adjacent operator: PO approval before winback</h2>
      <p>
        A $41k/mo B2B-light Shopify store selling to salon accounts ran winback to all lapsed buyers — including accounts with pending PO approvals and net-30 terms. Finance flagged inappropriate discount codes on active wholesale relationships. Suppression matrix addition: exclude customers tagged wholesale-pending or on payment terms before any promotional winback. Klaviyo handled tag logic natively; Sequenzy playbook accepted tag exclusion in agent prompt. Either works; neither works without ops documenting B2B edge cases in runbook appendix. Homepage ranking does not replace vertical SOP for account-type exclusions.
